\section{Describe the data}
\label{describe_data}

When the data are collected, a first step is to describe it with \texttt{describe\_data}.
Five types of plot, throught the \texttt{plot\_type} argument are possible:
\begin{itemize}
\item presence abscence matrix that represent the combinaison of germplasm $\times$ location
\item histogramm
\item barplot, where sd error are displayed
\item boxplot
\item interaction
\item biplot
\item radar
\end{itemize}
Then you must choose which factor to represent on the x axis (\texttt{x\_axis} argument),
the factor to display in color (\texttt{in\_col} argument), and of course the variable to describe (\texttt{vec\_variables} argument).

It is possible to tune the number of factor displayed (\texttt{nb\_parameters\_per\_plot\_x\_axis} and \texttt{nb\_parameters\_per\_plot\_in\_col} arguments) and the size of the labels regarding biplot and radar (\texttt{labels\_on} and \texttt{labels\_size} arguments).

\subsection{Format the data}

Get two data set to look at some examples
<<message=TRUE,cache=FALSE>>=
data("data_GxE")
data_GxE = format_data_PPBstats(data_GxE)

data("data_model_2")
data_model_2 = format_data_PPBstats(data_model_2)
@


\subsection{presence abscence matrix}

The presence absence matrix may be different from experimental design planned because of NA.
The plot represents the presence/absence matrix of G $\times$ E combinations.

<<message=TRUE,cache=FALSE>>=
p = describe_data(
  data_GxE, plot_type = "pam",
  vec_variables = c("y1", "y2")
  )
names(p)
p$y1
@
A score of 3 is for a given germplasm replicated three times in a given environement.

<<message=TRUE,cache=FALSE>>=
p = describe_data(
  data_model_2, plot_type = "pam",
  vec_variables = c("y1", "y2")
  )
p$y1
@
Here there are lots of 0 meaning that a lot of germplasm are no in at least two farms.
A score of 1 is for a given germplasm in a given environment.
A score of 2 is for a given germplasm replicated twice in a given environement.


